Goettling, Gary. Einstein&lt;U+2019&gt;s refrigerator Georgia Tech Alumni Magazine. 1998. Retrieved on 21 November 2005. Le&lt;U+00F3&gt; Szil&lt;U+00E1&gt;rd, a Hungarian physicist who later worked on the Manhattan Project, is credited with the discovery of the chain reaction↩
In September 2008 it was reported that Malcolm McCulloch of Oxford University was heading a three-year project to develop more robust appliances that could be used in locales lacking electricity, and that his team had completed a prototype Einstein refrigerator. He was quoted as saying that improving the design and changing the types of gases used might allow the design&lt;U+2019&gt;s efficiency to be quadrupled.↩
